entry.title: snap-groups: Move SplitViewOverviewSession to RootWindowController
entry.content:
This contains initial work to refactor SplitViewOverviewSession for

both tablet and clamshell mode. By moving it to RootWindowController,

both SplitViewController and SnapGroupController will be able to start

SplitViewOverviewSession without depending on `SplitViewController::

primary_window_|secondary_window_`.



Overview may outlive SplitViewOverviewSession. Workflow examples:

1. Start Overview -> drag a window to snap in split view -> start

SplitViewOverviewSession

2. Snap window in Snap Groups -> start SplitViewOverviewSession ->

start Overview

3. From SplitViewOverviewSession, close the window -> end split view

-> end SplitViewOverviewSession -> do not end Overview

4. End Overview -> always end SplitViewOverviewSession

For this reason, consumers should manually call `StartOverview()`,

then start SplitViewOverviewSession, but we can always end

SplitViewOverviewSession in `EndOverview()`.



This currently does nothing in tablet mode, a follow-up CL will refactor

adding/removing the window from overview to SplitViewOverviewSession.

entry.title: Move AutofillDataModel::guid_ into derived classes.
entry.content:
AutofillDataModel is the base class of AutofillProfile, CreditCard and

Iban. It declares a member guid_, which is supposed to be used as an

identifier.



For AutofillProfile, this works, since both kLocalOrSyncable and

kAccount profiles are identified by guids.



For CreditCard, local and server cards exist - but only local cards are

identified by guids. The dependency on AutofillDataModel::guid_ already

introduced bugs here: Even though server cards are not supposed to use

guids, the base class required initializing guid_ for all card types.

As a result, some code downstream now depends on them. See

crbug.com/1121806#c14 for details.



For Iban, only local ibans exist at the moment, but server ibans are

about to be introduced (crrev.com/c/4807711). Once again the guid_ of

the base class needs to be initialized unconditionally [1]. This way,

we might end up in the CreditCard situation.



Ideally, CreditCard and Iban shouldn't have a guid_ member, but a

variant of guid and server-id (or instrument-id), which is populated

depending on the RecordType. The accessors should CHECK() that they

are only called for the correct RecordTypes.



This CL makes a step towards this state by removing

AutofillDataModel::guid_ and re-declaring it in every derived class.

The change is kept a no-op and guid_ remains initialized for server

cards. A TODO is added.



This change thus:

- Takes a step towards resolving the id-ambiguity for CreditCards.

- Enables introducing the server iban identifier in a way that is

clearly separated from guids.

- Unblockes moving AutofillProfile from std::string guid to

base::Uuid. Efforts to do this (crrev.com/c/4177113) for all

AutofillDataModels were undertaken in the past, but ultimately

blocked by a hack in the CreditCard code (crrev.com/c/4277629).

By having a separate guid_ declaration for AutofillProfile, we can

at least partially move to base::Uuid. This should also enable

Ibans to migrate to base::Uuid.



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4807711/comment/b731f920_f88f4342/

entry.title: Reland "Fix first measurement time in CPUMeasurementMonitor::CPUMeasurement"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 50e6880647da6e072f1467546dc70dfdb6e5d972



It adjusts a CHECK to allow some slack due to rounding up after

division. Without the slack the CHECK is flaky when

SysInfo::NumberOfProcessors() is low, such as on Mac with CPU

security mitigations enabled, or on Chromecast test devices.



Original change's description:

> Fix first measurement time in CPUMeasurementMonitor::CPUMeasurement

>

> Now that CPUMeasurement records `last_measurement_time_` separately for

> each process, it's not possible for a "measurement interval" to start

> before the process was created.

>

> * Updates comments in MeasureAndDistributeCPUUsage(), which assumed

> measurements were always taken on a fixed schedule with a system-wide

> `last_measurement_time_`, to correctly describe processes measured on

> separate flexible schedules.

> * Initializes `last_measurement_time_` in the CPUMeasurement constructor

> when the first measurement is taken. The missed initialization was

> hidden because the process launch time was used as a fallback, which

> is not correct for processes that existed before CPUMeasurement

> objects were created by StartMonitoring().

> * Let time pass in unit tests between creating the process and

> StartMonitoring(). The bug was hidden by the mock clock in tests since

> the process launch time was the same time tick as the CPUMeasurement

> constructor, despite being created "before" StartMonitoring().

>

> Also adds more unit tests of error conditions.

>

entry.title: Revert "Re-land: CHECK that style and layout are not left dirty during lifecycle"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 78dcd4cdcb498ed2074435d709f752f88af080a3.



Reason for revert: Crash rate may be too high to launch, so reverting while we investigate ways to mitigate this.



Original change's description:

> Re-land: CHECK that style and layout are not left dirty during lifecycle

>

> The first iteration of this patch, https://crrev.com/1192759, was

> reverted due to scroll animations leaving style and layout dirty

> (https://crbug.com/1478009). This turns out to be working as intended

> so this patch moves the cleanliness check below

> `RunScrollSnapshotClientSteps`.

>

> Original change description below:

> `LocalFrameView::UpdateLifecyclePhasesInternal` is responsible for

> running the lifecycle and uses the following high-level pattern:

> while (true) {

> RunStyleAndLayoutLifecyclePhases();

>

> bool needs_to_repeat_lifecycle = RunStepA();

> if (needs_to_repeat_lifecycle) { continue; }

>

> bool needs_to_repeat_lifecycle = RunStepB();

> if (needs_to_repeat_lifecycle) { continue; }

> ...

> }

> Each step expects clean style and layout, and if a step dirties style

> or layout, it should re-start the lifecycle. This patch adds CHECKs for

> many of the lifecycle steps which ensures style and layout are not left

> dirty. These checks are added inside functions when possible, to

> provide more helpful crash stacks.

entry.title: [wptrunner] Open `results.html` for all initial failures
entry.content:
`run_web_tests.py` will still open `results.html` if there are any

failures in the initial round [1], even if those failures aren't

regressions because they're listed in `TestExpectations`. (Technically,

expected subtest FAIL lines won't open `results.html` because baseline

matches are not considered failures.)



Change `run_wpt_tests.py` to behave similarly (modulo expected subtest

failures, which `--no-show-results` can deactivate). Since a regression

implies an initial failure, the existing `num_regressions` check is now

redundant and can be removed.



[1]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/tools/blinkpy/web_tests/controllers/manager.py;l=225;drc=23093a316692fa671371b038045f60ed1e4ad7b2;bpv=0;bpt=0

entry.title: [Android][CredMan] Introduce java bridge for No-Passkeys sheet
entry.content:
The bridge only connects to native so far. Since there is no real

showing/dismissing happening, any call leads to a dismissal so that

using the bridge would be save already since clean-up is guaranteed.



The bridge accepts context and bottomsheet controller (for the

view). All passed objects are weak since they may be invalidated

by the time they are needed. A null dependency is equivalent to

an invalidated dependency.

Passing them as weak ensures that the construction always succeeds

and never fails to create a java-bridge.

The coordinator/mediator can then handle the absence of a

dependency (spoiler: it will do nothing but still ensure the proper

clean-up ... but this logic doesn't belong in the bridge.)

entry.title: Fix race condition in a few tests in URLLoaderTest
entry.content:
This is the same race condition that was earlier patched in

URLLoaderTest.ClientAuthCertificateWith(Invalid|Valid)Signature. See CL

referenced.



This patch fixes a race condition within the URLLoader gtests that

causes tests to fail. Sometimes url_loader is nullptr and sometimes

certificates has been requested even though the test expects different.



The reason for this race condition relates to the usage of

RunLoop::RunUntilIdle. Before, the test did the following:



1. The tests creates an URLLoader that requests a resource from

EmbeddedTestServer.

2. The test does RunLoop::RunUntilIdle

3. The test checks that URLLoader has not been deleted, which is made

upon request completion.



Most of the times, this succeeds. Sometimes it does not, mostly on

slower systems or on systems under heavy load. I think the reason is

that the test makes an incorrect assumption with regards to

RunLoop::RunUntilIdle and how threads are scheduled on an OS. What I

think happens is:



1. The network request to EmbeddedTestServer is made from the test main

thread.

2. The OS can context switch away from the test main thread before the

task system has reached an idle state.

3. The IO thread of EmbeddedTestServer responds to the request made by

URLLoader.

4. When the test thread is again scheduled, it has new data to fetch

from the server, triggering new tasks and completing the URL load.

This causes the checks that no progress on the URL request has been

made to fail.



This patch removes checks for temporary state that cannot be guaranteed

within the tests and instead makes the tests solely rely on expected

end-state, for which there's no race condition.
